In our most recent blog post, Max Cole @maxwcole shares his takeaway from last week's Legal Geek and reflects on the differences he's seen as it grows in size and influence. #legalgeek #legaltechnology https://www. autto.io/legal-geek-201 8-working-at-the-small-stuff/ …
We have a rule and follow it best we can: We keep our APIs in sync with the front end capabilities. Worth it!
Hallelujah! The opportunities associated with back-end integration are immense. Great to see increasing number of players adopted inbound and outbound API strategies as well to add value for clients
Honestly puzzled that people still do not build API-first in 2018.
Like many things, it’s easy to do a mediocre version
Not many awards ceremonies for APIs right?
It involves constant effort. We have 2 full teams working on our API backlog and enhancements.

I remember managing roadmaps for API and making sure new features/infrastructure changes didn’t break the APIs. Tough gig! People saying APIs are easy make me think they have yet to deploy other than in theory.
Took us years of work at this before we got to a robust API (though - like pretty much any feature - we continue to work at it)
wow ... we finally hit the Era of the API. It's been a long time coming. Let's make them robust and documented ( https:// github.com/AlexHamilton/L awTech-Glossary … )

The best thing working here is having the inside track on the solutions in this field your team (and with wider tech and lawyer teams) pull together using the 'toolkit' for real problems. Sitting near James here is London is a privilege and massive learning experience.
Exactly.. our ‘hub’ concept is driven by API lead development within the ecosystem. Only those with the api’s can connect.
We put a lot of effort into @KiraSystems API for this reason - to allow others to easily connect in
Maybe because what lawyers need to know/do about change today is no different than it was 5 years ago.
Also helps with change management. Easier to get customers to adopt when you can pick and choose functionality to solve their specific use case.
Spectrum of Functionality - the short version of last tweet.

We’ve found the open platform that allows easy connections to an entire ecosystem of tech functionality (including multiple layers of AI) is superior to standalone products. Can tailor a solution to a grand spectrum of clients by combining various elements.
Why is this and everything below it from 5 years ago? Show me something new

Me quoting you at ReInvent Law 2014 in my improving" talk. 4 years later and the same discussion was being had around #LegalGeek . Most agreeing we need to improve incrementally but some saying that was a "tired and self-defeating mantra". We need you back jib jabbing again

#throwback Brian. Was that Reinvent? That was a surreal event too. Where did that go? Oh yeah, all hyped out. Forgive me if I’m not that responsive I don’t really “do” Legal jib jab on here anymore although it’s still great fun to watch. Love a conference hashtag.

As @jonb1966 once said: lawyers are trying to reinvent themselves into something they will never be instead of improving on what they actually are. Something valuable that is just a bit broken and well worth fixing. Someone needs rescue them. http:// thetimeblawg.com/2014/07/04/imp roving-for-reinvent-law-london-2014/ …
There’s creating a buzz (added to the 5,000 other buzzes out there at any given time) and there’s creating companies. Those are two very different things.
Mark’s presentation on Skinny Law before Robot Law is spot in still half a decade later (just watched it back)

There’s results and measurables in taking tiny steps - culture, people etc. Like the rower guy taking about daily improvements. The snake oil person is selling the magic blue pill (with no idea of how it works or not). Boring includes vision, foundations and tech well implemented

Some thoughts on the scope of the #lawtech market. By me @AuttoIO . Thanks to @ArtificialLawya https:// twitter.com/ArtificialLawy a/status/1054643332431970304 …

Agreed. Ease of use is paramount to adoption. And maybe especially so in an underserved tech market like legal. Nail the UX around AI *cough* ML *cough* and you have something special. Too often I think companies focus too much on the tech and not the experience.

Not necessarily a new phenomenon. Historical and fictional accounts of the British navy often mention the sea lawyer" phenomenon amongst the crew. And I just learned that even gamers have their own version - https:// en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rules_law yer …"

We Are All Lawyers Now – The Rise of the Legalish @AuttoIO via @ArtificialLawya I love the legalish concept + implications discussed. Not sure US bar regulators will feel the same! Sadly, they may well think legalish = UPL
Amen, brother. You hit the trifecta for legal tech apps. 1) Easy onboarding and use, (2) “manyX-better-than-current-solution” value delivery and (3) bulletproof (tables stakes, really) tech.
But data isn’t just numbers hence my comment about following the data in investigative journalism.
True: it’s easy to mislead with numbers.
I suspect a lot of the failure is just non-adoption. Adoption can be a battle that frequently takes time and effort. I wonder if you’d get any more interesting failures - eg mistakes in work product.

Yep, I wrote about this last year but may have not be innovative enough at the time. The history of technology in Legal is actually pretty positive, apart from the Microsoft Word thing ... https://www. linkedin.com/pulse/state-ai -nation-legal-part-3-alex-g-smith …

A lot of #legaltech is a variation on a mainstream tech product which is why I suggested historical context is important. Google for work has a lot of collaboration tools but law loves Microsoft. Not to mention that people tech is what law needs - biggest ops cost & inefficiency

Many of my former colleagues are in innovation/product teams in other industries doing systematic innovation/transformation at scale, it's cool, it's agile, it's real. It's also hard, about people, process and cultural change. There are of course challenges and will take time.

Hopefully this week is us moving onto a new phase, this past phase has not been good. In fact most of this has been a distraction, most of what we heard at Legal Geek is about process, people, continual improvement, designing the service delivered to rapidly changing industries

It's the way of the world now, esp as there will be a lot of unpicking of AI/tech failures to date and should be great exemplars/real use cases of AI that lawyers/ethics etc can build on. No shortage of choices at the present time. Old principles/skills with new tools.
Isn’t “follow the data” the only way to have real investigative journalism? How else can you do it?

I have constantly referenced (along with Ben Gardner) the Panama Papers story and the pragmatic + creative use of discovery tech as one of the best pieces of legal tech" as well as a great story of team work and trust. The drive to 'follow the data' in journalism is awesome"

Well there are some serious things wrong in technology that awesome data driven/'follow the data' reporters (who are who i use as exemplars for investigative future lawyers) are doing right now ... like whether the Brexit election was 'hacked'. Carole and team are amazing.
Obviously @ZachAbramowitz gets a pass on the critique as he sees it!

Open + ecosystem= exciting and different user centered future This always brings me back to what Microsoft has done and is doing.. open and ecosystem mindset is a key differentiator Like you said gives the user options and flexibility.

Yep, most of the tech reporters missed it because it’s doesnt fit into a labelled bucket. But the open and ecosystem is the key part as is allowing customers to be creative on the platform. The recent RelativityFest community award nominees list was hugely creative - @agiuslaw
Key word here is “open”

Relativity and a few others are now killing outside of eDiscovery by having an open ecosystem. In contract review now ... @bryon_z @ChuckyConnor ... when you break tech into a problem solving toolkit rather that ‘hype battles’ you come to real solutions.
I’m hoping that evolution will be from collecting badges to stories of execution, adoption, change and benefit along the value chain.

Totally agree. Not sure why so many trying to build new document automation technology. We were lawyers who just wanted to use one, and chose @HotDocsGroup . The value is in what you can do with it, (the outcomes you can generate) not in the technology itself.

Do you really think that the market is big enough for yet another doc automation SW? Don’t understand the differentiation there. Especially since in many cases lawyers arent really using them.. I’m always amazed that people are still creating more “new” doc automation tools.

Some spaces not so big especially if you want a case management system that seamlessly integrates with your accounts system and the latter needs to be tailored to local law society rules. New players in such markets will have their work cut out if they just have a CMS on offer.

Multiple companies can do well in a big space. Even with @relativityHQ killing it in large-scale eDiscovery, it seems like a bunch of others have built / are building valuable businesses here (eg, @logikcull @everlaw @csdisco , plus legacy ones)

And many are reinventing the wheel without realising it. Many don't research what is already on the market and what they are up against with their shiny new document automation system or other similar toys. Many trying to sell to a market that already has what they are selling.
Maybe point of multiple tools doing the same thing is to test different user experiences.

Agree, the challenge is change management. The winners will be those tools that are easy to onboard and use, deliver value, and comply with table stakes standards. How many of the startups out there are achieving all of these things? Very difficult to achieve in MVP.
I’m all for nearly all our competitors going away! kidding!
Lots of companies can exist, though many are likely still trying to get traction.

The point of having hundreds of doc automation companies is unknown to me.I believe the market is overly saturated w/ this and the funny thing is that most lawyers don’t actually use it.most lawyers doing the hard work don’t think legaltech is special they’re too busy. Vendors..

Could agree more the hype probably sinks more #legaltech than it sells, enjoyed @nwaisb 's presentation on Hype @wearelegalgeek We should be talking more about change mgmt in legal and less about shiny tech
